oakcurric:unit-669
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Fossil evidence, selective breeding and explaining evolution"@en ;
  curric:slug "fossil-evidence-selective-breeding-and-explaining-evolution" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores evidence for evolution, including fossils and antibiotic
  resistance. It covers selective breeding, Darwin and Wallace’s contributions to natural
  selection, and evolution as changes in inherited traits over time. It also examines how
  scientific theories evolve over time."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ prior learning from Adaptations, competition,
  natural selection and evolution, where they explored how organisms adapt and evolve based on
  environmental pressures. It deepens their understanding by focusing on fossil evidence and
  selective breeding, illustrating how these processes provide insight into evolutionary change
  over time. This prepares pupils for the next unit, Variation and natural selection at the
  genetic level, where they will explore the genetic mechanisms driving evolution, reinforcing
  their understanding of evolutionary biology.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-669-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-669-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-669-3 ,
